[src:pants-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:pants-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:pants-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:pants-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] An automated incremental computing tool is a specialised program analysis tool for optimization.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Some approaches to incremental computing are specialized, while others are general purpose.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Specialized approaches require the programmer to explicitly specify the algorithms and data structures that will be used to preserve unchanged sub-calculations.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] General-purpose approaches, on the other hand, use language, compiler, or algorithmic techniques to give incremental behavior to otherwise non-incremental programs.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Given a computation $C=f(x_{1},x_{2},\dots x_{n})$ and a potential change $x_{j}:=\Delta _{x_{j}}$ , we can insert code before the change occurs (the pre-derivative) and after the change (the post-derivative) to update the value of C faster than rerunning f .
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Paige has written down a list of rules for formal differentiation of programs in SUBSETL.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] In database systems such as DBToaster, views are defined with relational algebra.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] *Incremental view maintenance* statically analyzes relational algebra to create update rules that quickly maintain the view in the presence of small updates, such as insertion of a row.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Incremental computation can be achieved by building a dependency graph of all the data elements that may need to be recalculated, and their dependencies.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] The elements that need to be updated when a single element changes are given by the transitive closure of the dependency relation of the graph.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] In other words, if there is a path from the changed element to another element, the latter may be updated (depending on whether the change eventually reaches the element).
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] The dependency graph may need to be updated as dependencies change, or as elements are added to, or removed from, the system.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] It is used internally by the implementation, and does not typically need to be displayed to the user.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] Partial evaluation can be combined with other incremental computing techniques.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] With cycles in the dependency graph, a single pass through the graph may not be sufficient to reach a fixed point.
[src:pants-build/incremental-computing] In some cases, complete re-evaluation of a system is semantically equivalent to incremental evaluation, and may be more efficient in practice if not in theory.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:pants-build/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:pants-build/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:pants-build/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:pants-build/software-build] A **software build** is the process of converting source code files into standalone software artifact(s) that can be run on a computer, or the result of doing so.
[src:pants-build/software-build] In include functions such as version control, code quality analysis, compilation, and linking.
[src:pants-build/software-build] In software production, builds optimize software for performance and distribution, packaging into formats such as '.*exe'; '.deb'; '.apk'*.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The build process often employs specialized tools such as CMake, Make, or Gradle, and integrates with automation systems including Jenkins or GitHub Actions.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Despite advancements, challenges such as dependency conflicts, platform compatibility, and long compile times, remain problems.
[src:pants-build/software-build] In software development, building software is an end-to-end process that involves many distinct functions.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Some of these functions are described below.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The version control function carries out activities such as workspace creation and updating, baselining and reporting.
[src:pants-build/software-build] It creates an environment for the build process to run in and captures metadata about the inputs and output of the build process to ensure repeatability and reliability.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Tools such as Git, AccuRev or StarTeam help with these tasks by offering tools to tag specific points in history as being important, and more.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Also known as static program analysis/static code analysis this function is responsible for checking that developers have adhered to the seven axes of code quality: comments, unit tests, duplication, complexity, coding rules, potential bugs and architecture & design.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Ensuring a project has high-quality code results in fewer bugs and influences nonfunctional requirements such as maintainability, extensibility and readability; which have a direct impact on the ROI for a business.
[src:pants-build/software-build] This is only a small feature of managing the build process.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The compilation function turns source files into directly executable or intermediate objects.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Not every project will require this function.
[src:pants-build/software-build] While for simple programs the process consists of a single file being compiled, for complex software the source code may consist of many files and may be combined in different ways to produce many different versions.
[src:pants-build/software-build] A linker or link editor is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:pants-build/software-build] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:pants-build/software-build] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The process of building a computer program is usually managed by a build tool, a program that coordinates and controls other programs.
[src:pants-build/software-build] Examples of such a program are make, Gradle, Ant, Maven, Rake, SCons and Phing.
[src:pants-build/software-build] The build utility typically needs to compile the various files, in the correct order.
[src:pants-build/software-build] If the source code in a particular file has not changed then it may not need to be recompiled ("may not" rather than "need not" because it may itself depend on other files that have changed).
[src:pants-build/software-build] Sophisticated build utilities and linkers attempt to refrain from recompiling code that does not need it, to shorten the time required to complete the build.
[src:pants-build/software-build] A more complex process may involve other programs producing code or data as part of the build process and software.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants is a fast, scalable, user-friendly build system for codebases of all sizes.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] It's currently focused on Python, Go, Java, Scala, Kotlin, Shell, and Docker, with support for other languages and frameworks coming soon.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Here you'll find guides to help you get started with Pants, comprehensive documentation on how to configure, run and customize Pants, and information on how to get help from the Pants community.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] A lot of effort has gone into making Pants easy to adopt, easy to use and easy to extend.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants requires very minimal BUILD file metadata/boilerplate.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] It uses a combination of static analysis and sensible defaults to infer most of that information on the fly.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] So your BUILD files can be very minimal — and even those can be generated and updated for you!
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants operates, underneath it all, at the file level.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] So even if you have fine-grained dependency tangles (or even cycles!) that prevent you from creating modular BUILD targets and dependencies, Pants can work with that.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants has a rich plugin API that uses idiomatic async Python 3, in case you need any customizations.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] In fact the built-in rules use that same API.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants natively speaks git, so you can do things like "run all the tests affected by changes between main and my current branch".
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] You'll find no subsets like Starlark here.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants empowers you with full support for Python.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants supports Python, Docker, Go, Java, Kotlin, Pex, Protodoc, Scala, Shell, Thrift, Protobuf, Helm, many linting and formatting tools, packaging, coverage, and more.
[src:pants-build/www-pantsbuild-org] Pants community is welcoming, quick to answer questions, and genuinely interested in your thoughts and contributions.
